social_posts.post_text: A couple of years ago on opening day, I hiked through some hip deep snow banks to walk Petey on the beach where I was pretty sure no one would think we were deer. After a couple weeks dressing myself and the dogs in high-vis colors, carefully planning walk times and locations, and chasing them away from thoughtlessly discarded offal, I’m celebrating closing day. I hope all the ethical hunters had a successful season, and I hope the rest of the a$$hats with guns in the woods either didn’t get anything or it tastes terrible if they did.
Don't make me angry. You wouldn't like me when I'm angry. Au contraire, lakeshore.

It’s December and it’s dark and we need some snow to brighten things up. Both the landscape and my mood. Last year I learned how to skate ski, fell in love with it, and my addictive personality racked up many kilometers. I’m ready to click in and get gliding, and pretend that the days are longer than they are. How do you get through these dark months?
Early winter beach textures are my love language.

It’s beach season at Point Betsie. Winter is my favorite time to visit this lighthouse. It can change so dramatically between visits depending on how cold and windy it’s been. Hoping this is a good ice year!

Traverse City is off to a slow snow start this December. It’s brown and gray in town (although this did afford for the opportunity to remove leaves that had gotten buried under November snow), and lightly dusted in the hills outside town. We have a little storm headed our way later this week, and I’m doing my best snow dance moves. I’d bait you all with “a million likes and I’ll show you the dance,” but a million likes isn’t happening, and if it does I’m just posting Tom Cruise from Risky Business. Photo is from a snow storm in early December 2019. Daydreams of long days on skis are current. Have a great week friends!
Ahhhhh. *That’s* what I’m talking about ❄️💙❄️
Signs point to a white Christmas and I’m ready to celebrate ❄️🎄
In the midst of winter, I found there was, within me, an invincible summer. -Albert Camus
May the arrival of winter chase the darkness away. Happy solstice my friends.
Making Christmas!
The calm before the storm. I hope everyone has milk and bread, and plenty of TP from the 2020 hoarding still. In all seriousness, I hope power stays on and y’all drive safe.
Merry Christmas Eve. Wishing you all peace, love, and hope.

I left Michigan last week before the bad (aka good) weather arrived, but I did get to spend time inside with my family through windchills in  the -35° range. Grateful for the memories (posted some in my stories), but now of you need me you can find me on the trail 🎿

Winter is my favorite time to visit the Mackinac Bridge. Who goes to the island in the winter? Might be time for me to get over there and do a combo trip. Got any tips for me? I’m all ears. Plus eyes, nose, and the rest 🙃

Hope the last day of the year has been beachy. I mean peachy. I mean nice. Posting something cheeky in my stories because I just remembered it. Is that cryptic? A little. Is it worth looking at? Probably not. Happy New Year anyway!

I love the way a thick blanket of snow smooths over all the rough edges, and how nothing looks more appropriate to the landscape than a red barn tucked anchored by some pines under a blue sky. *not a recent photo, obviously*

We have neither snow nor sun, though I suppose we’ve had some rain, so I guess there’s still challenges for mail delivery. I’m pouting about the weather, because I’m good at that kind of adulting, but I sneaked in a great ski day so this image from February suits my state of mind. Happy weekend friends!

La Niña is being a real B so sun and snow have been in short supply. Plenty of both in the archives! How are you managing the seasonal depression? I’m super grouchy about conditions, but I’ve been getting outside with friends, and that really keeps me from sliding too far downhill.

Dear Diary,
It’s been 16 days since I’ve seen sunshine. Last night I did catch a glimpse of sunset, but it was really only about a minute, so even though it was nice, I don’t think that counts. We are all complaining about it like it will change things. We all know it won’t, but we can’t stop ourselves. I keep hoping for brighter days, but whining is as bright as it gets. That’s all for now.
Wishing you a bright sunshiny day! I’m feeling very refreshed after many k in these conditions yesterday 💙🌞❄️
Those moody days when the sun breaks through and electrifies the lake 🤩
Maybe after this weekend’s cooler temps the lakeshore will offer us some ice sculptures!

The sunrise was a welcome change from the oppressive grays we’ve had almost continuously since around Thanksgiving. It can be a tough time of year. Even though I’m outside for some kind of activity nearly every day, it’s obvious how heavy the clouds have been when the sun shines and uplifts your entire soul when it does. I found myself singing “you are my sunshine” while out hiking today, which made today a good day indeed. Anyone else moved to song lately?

It’s a short season. I might be addicted. I learned how to freestyle Nordic ski (aka skate ski) just over a year ago. Now I’m training for a big personal goal. How big? Check my stories for a hint. I’ve always enjoyed the seasons, but I love moving in this way so much that I want more winter. I know. I know. Anyway, what’s your favorite way to move? Keep it PG 😉

It’s finally wintering pretty well (for a few days at least) but I spliced together a few minutes of snorkeling footage from our recent trip to Jamaica. I offer what I think are some genuinely helpful tips if you’re not already an experienced snorkeler 🐠

Pyramid Point is one of the most popular hikes in the dunes, often with overflowing parking in the warmer months. It’s no less incredible in the winter - maybe even more with the stark white snow against the rich lake blues - but with smaller crowds. Pack a hot chocolate, or plan a stop at @grocersdaughter for a warm up after! (Grocer’s Daughter has no idea I’m saying this; they just have really excellent hot chocolate).

Sometimes it winters hard in northern Michigan. I’m not after a brutal polar vortex winter, but this extended shoulder season is for the birds. Literally - I’ve seen lots of flocks of Canada geese on the wing the last few days ❄️🐦
Back in the days when Petey was an only dog, and winter was cold enough for Lake Michigan to freeze. And despite my love for winter, I can’t find it in me to complain about today’s warm sunshine.
Still posting photos, just not here so much.
Snowy walk zoomies
The aurora was considerate enough to show before my bedtime 🤪💚
Larger, stiller, longer versions with captions and more, over there ❤️
Last week’s collection. Trying to figure out how to balance my efforts. 🙃

Last week I shared a collection of images from the redwood forests in Northern California. The uncropped photos are up on my patreon. I would love to return to this area for more extensive coastal and woodland exploration…but it’s more desert time for me this spring.
Images from the #redwoods 💚💚💚
Happy vernal equinox! Really hoping today isn’t a harbinger for the rest of the season. Unless you had a great day, and then I hope you experience more of the same. I’m hoping things trend upward 🤪

Yesterday we learned that our very good boy Petey likely has a hemangiosarcoma in his heart. You can google it, but it’s bad news. The worst. My emotions keep spilling out my eyes, and down my cheeks, and my appetite is on a hiatus. Thankfully, although he’s being picky about what he wants, Petey’s appetite is currently good. And so is the rest of him; all of his blood work and basically everything looks healthy as can be. There’s a small tiny chance that the bleeding into his pericardium was not from a tumor, but I’m not hanging my hopes on that unlikelihood. Regardless, he will have as many good days as he we can give him, and we will not be pursuing anything heroic. 💔🐶

I started photographing the aurora right on the State Park beach in Traverse City the other night, because it’s close to home with a good view of the northern sky. It’s still a little close to town for light pollution, but it’s a good place to see what’s up. Which I have to think is what this swan was trying to determine. I have 37 shots with this dude because I was so enamored of its calm presence. Watching me watching you 💚 Also, patrons you just got a high resolution copy of this and 8 more (not of the swan) in your emails ☺️

I will keep this brief because it’s all I can muster right now - but I know many of you have noticed my absence and wondered. We said goodbye to our best good boy Petey on Thursday evening. I’ll post more when my emotions have settled some. Luck put us in a cottage on Lake Michigan this weekend, and we’ve been hanging out with Juniper, who is doing well currently but we expect some sadness when we get back home. 💔🐶
ICYMI! Photos of the week. Survived a long run in the Grand Canyon, and it looks like I’m gonna make it through wisdom tooth extraction as well. GC adventure coming soon!
In memory of those who have died serving our country.

What a weekend! Pictured Rocks is one of my happy places. More details and photos coming soon to my patreon (in bio). #picturedrocks #grandmarais #logslideoverlook #twelvemilebeach #beaverbasin #chapelrock #grandportalpoint #mosquitoriver #munisingfalls #sandpoint #munising
Juniper has discovered the joy of frisbees. She’s been a fan of sticks and balls (Hahaha! That sounds inappropriate!) for a long time, but frisbee might be her favorite.
Some things that seem too good to be true aren’t.
Happy Solstice. Juniper and I celebrated the longest day(light) of the year in true Michigander style by going to the beach. 🩵🏖️☀️

I storied this photo of the beach yesterday morning after my swim. I had a request to post it to my feed because it shows so much Lake Michigan character, so here it is. Just a quick grab with my phone because the conditions were pristine, which didn’t happen many times at all last year. Happy Friday my friends!
My tour guide advice when asked “Where should I go?” More in the link in my bio 👌
I’m waiting on feedback from my patrons, but these are coming soon!

I got all excited about fall, and revisited a favorite hike in the UP. My Patreon is going to see lots of images from this adventure (viewable by everyone!). Also, Calendars are officially under production right here in Traverse City.
I meant to post this last night, because this shot was taken 8 years ago, yesterday. 🌝
Blue hour on the Garden Peninsula #upperpeninsula #lakemichigan
Just an iPhone shot, so it’s a rare thing on my feed that’s not available for large prints, but it’s too pretty to leave behind in my stories. I’m over here holding fall’s beer 😳💛
Magical run in the Sleeping Bear Dunes today. Fall colors showing off, lake effect snow blowing in on dramatic clouds. Ahhhh. ☺️🍁❄️ #sleepingbeardunes #fallcolors

Here until they aren’t! In my store, which is linked in my bio, and I’ll add a link to my stories. Side note: there’s an Easter egg in the calendars, but it’s printed exactly two months early, and I didn’t notice until today 🫠
Traverse City showing off on this warm November day 🫶
Captured this freezing lake yesterday while getting my first kicks of the season 🎿 Hard to believe that it was second summer just a couple weeks ago and I was out on the bay windsurfing 😵‍💫

Note: I’ll be shipping calendars out again tomorrow morning if you want to add to the post office stack 😉

Even on breezy days, if you know which way the wind is blowing, you can find a place of stillness. This could either be a metaphor for life, or one of those Instagram vs reality things. Or just a photo tip 😉 Anyway, happy Friday - I hope you find some calm in the chaos.
Thank you all for your support! Calendars have all shipped (except the few that are ready for local pickup)!
What’s better: getting into bed with freshly washed sheets, or waking up to a fresh blanket of snow?
Perhaps Old Man Winter’s spirit is embodied by this majestic tree on the top of this knoll. The evidence speaks for itself.
Hope you make the most of this shortest day of the year. Unless you’re in the southern hemisphere, and then I hope you enjoy this longest day of the year because winter is coming.

A December beach scene from Leelanau County. The fall colors on the right are courtesy of oaks that stubbornly hold their leaves, and pines that are evergreen. Happy day after the solstice. May your days be merry and bright!
Dreaming of a white Christmas ☃️🎄
Let there be lights
Wishing you a cozy Christmas! ❤️🎄

Frankfort Ice Bridge. More detailed story on my patreon, which you can see for free at any time via the link in my bio.
And a Happy New Year 💚💜🩷
